	(113,1,'2014-02-14 10:28:45','2014-02-14 10:28:45','','Ada Lovelace','first considered programmer','inherit','open','open','','adalovelace_feature','','','2014-02-14 10:28:45','2014-02-14 10:28:45','',91,'http://rachellesalvadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/AdaLovelace_Feature.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),
	(114,1,'2014-02-14 11:00:15','2014-02-14 11:00:15','I always see an article about women and programming, women and technology, or something about women and computer and how the world should attract women to code but I never knew/heard/read that the first considered programmer is a woman. Yes, men. A woman who is also a mother of three.\r\n\r\nLady Ada Lovelace.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://rachellesalvadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/ada.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-109\" alt=\"ada\" src=\"http://rachellesalvadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/ada.jpg\" width=\"402\" height=\"402\" /></a>\r\n\r\nI remember reading an article about giving women someone to look up to in tech industry, guess what? They never mention the mother of programming. I was shocked when i first heard of her because I\'ve never seen an article that aims to inspire women to code mentioned her. Personally, I thought that the first programmer was a male. I don\'t know if it is true but it seems that not most programmers know about her. (or I don\'t know if its just me because you know,Â  I\'m still at the very beginning stage)\r\n\r\nIf programmers or their community really want to inspire women to code as they are claiming,Â  they need Ada Lovelace. It\'s not that we (women) will try to be a math genius as she was or what, but it is always a good feeling that if she did it, we can as well. And this can be a positive attitude for women to actually try. Plus, it seems like she is fashionable, elegant and still manages to live like a woman should and would want.\r\n\r\nProgramming always has this image in us that people or girls who only do it are boring, dull and anti-socials. Look! She seems beautiful, elegant and graceful.\r\n\r\nIts an issue today that women are leaving the tech world. Why? Because there is a feeling that we don\'t belong. Before I learn the first language that I use today, coding was like a language that alien speaks. Surely not English like in the movies. The reason why there are less and less women in this field is because I though it is obvious that it is a guy thing.\r\n\r\nBut when i discovered Lady Ada, I\'m literally confused.It gives me a little bit of confidence that I can learn and understand how to program, like a pro (Okay. Maybe not like a pro but still can program) .\r\n\r\nSeriously, she could be what we(girls) need to know about and not this popular information that girls are actually abandoning the tech community because to be honest, its pressuring to know that there is only going to be 2-3 girls in the area where you work and that you guys expect more from you.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','','','inherit','open','open','','91-revision-v1','','','2014-02-14 11:00:15','2014-02-14 11:00:15','',91,'http://rachellesalvadora.com/?p=114',0,'revision','',0),
