	(142,1,'2014-05-22 02:12:00','2014-05-22 02:12:00','If you don\'t have any idea how programming works, <a href=\"http://scratch.mit.edu\">scratch</a> is a good place to start. Don\'t worry, five years old kids use this.\r\n\r\nWell, I spent more than 20 hours onÂ  it. But that was me. I don\'t know what I am doing at first. I had 5 tries before i finally knew what i wanted to do. I wanted to do something more but I was restricted with time limit as I am doing it for cs50.\r\n\r\nI didn\'t really know what I was doing on the first try. Just trying to figure out the loops, conditions, etc. They\'re like puzzle pieces for me. The loops/conditions/statements shouldÂ  have to be implemented on the right timing and the right places.\r\n\r\nFor the no coding experience like me, scratch is like something thats from heavens above. No, I\'m not exaggerating. At least for me, as without technical background or anything like that. I really see it as the best way to start my way to programming. Plus it\'s fun.\r\n\r\nLets divide them into 4 parts so I can explain them better. The planning,Â  sprites,Â  scripts and the final product.\r\n\r\n<strong>Planning</strong>\r\n\r\nI was just starting to know about programming, so what I did is something that I can easily implement. I am a 90\'s kid so I picked something out of what i played in the family computer. I tried the hard ones. I ended up not finishing the projects. So I went easy on myself and went with something I can finish.\r\n\r\n<strong>Sprites</strong>\r\n\r\nAll the objects that you can see in a scratch project is called sprite. You can make your own, upload it, or you can use the sprites provided by scratch. There\'s a lot if you only look into it. You can edit them or resize them. You can change their colors as well. Just name your spritesÂ relative to how it looks or how it functions as and simple as possible. You\'ll thank yourself when you\'re doing the scripts. Make the sizes of the sprites base on how many sprites you wanted to put in the stage at one point.\r\n\r\nWhat I did at first was, i tried to use the sprites that\'s in scratch library. I didn\'t edit them, i just put them in the stage. They are so big though that I can only fit in a lot less than what I was planning. I wanna get rid of them as quick as possible so I just abandoned the project and then just tried again.\r\n\r\nI know now that i have to edit the sprites first. And so i tried to learn how to resize the sprites, change the colors, how to make it look like the catÂ  is walking and stuff like that. Until I realized that i have to set up the sprites first on the stage before I put in the scripts.\r\n\r\n<strong>Scripts</strong>\r\n\r\nAfter setting up the sprites in the stage, i know now when i want the ball to move, which direction I wanted it to go and what happens when it encounters other sprites and when it hits the edge of the stage. Although this part is time consuming, its easy because i planned my project properly and setting up the sprites first helped a lot because it became easier for me to see and identify what each of the sprite does.\r\n\r\nYou can also put in sound effects or make the sprites say something through texts or actual sounds.\r\n\r\n<strong>Final Product</strong>\r\n\r\nThis is the link to my <a href=\"http://scratch.mit.edu/projects/16765812/\">scratch project</a>.\r\n\r\nMy project isn\'t the best. It has bugs that I don\'t know how to fix. I tried to fix it but it just ruin my project more. So I let it be. Although I\'m worried that It might not pass because of the bugs. I shared it and I still submitted it. I\'m not that confident about the product of my problem set 0 but it is better than what I am expecting.\r\n\r\nIt was graded after 2 weeks with 1.0. I can\'t explain how happy I was. Although I didn\'t post it on cs50 group on Facebook because I am too shy, I showed it to Julian and he was happy with it and showed it to his friend. It feels so good to know that he is proud of me.\r\n\r\nWell, its just the start of cs50. And I\'m about to write actual codes soon after it. I\'m excited and nervous at the same time. :D\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBtw, this could be a helpful video link of <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BYrr8262UUs&amp;list=PL289FE8CA0392401A\">scratch tutorials</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Pset 0','','inherit','open','open','','126-revision-v1','','','2014-05-22 02:12:00','2014-05-22 02:12:00','',126,'http://rachellesalvadora.com/?p=142',0,'revision','',0),
	(143,1,'2014-05-22 02:13:07','2014-05-22 02:13:07','If you don\'t have any idea how programming works, <a href=\"http://scratch.mit.edu\">scratch</a> is a good place to start. Don\'t worry, five years old kids use this.\r\n\r\nWell, I spent more than 20 hours onÂ  it. But that was me. I don\'t know what I am doing at first. I had 5 tries before i finally knew what i wanted to do. I wanted to do something more but I was restricted with time limit as I am doing it for cs50.\r\n\r\nI didn\'t really know what I was doing on the first try. Just trying to figure out the loops, conditions, etc. They\'re like puzzle pieces for me. The loops/conditions/statements shouldÂ  have to be implemented on the right timing and the right places.\r\n\r\nFor the no coding experience like me, scratch is like something thats from heavens above. No, I\'m not exaggerating. At least for me, as without technical background or anything like that. I really see it as the best way to start my way to programming. Plus it\'s fun.\r\n\r\nLets divide them into 4 parts so I can explain them better. The planning,Â  sprites,Â  scripts and the final product.\r\n\r\n<strong>Planning</strong>\r\n\r\nI was just starting to know about programming, so what I did is something that I can easily implement. I am a 90\'s kid so I picked something out of what i played in the family computer. I tried the hard ones. I ended up not finishing the projects. So I went easy on myself and went with something I can finish.\r\n\r\n<strong>Sprites</strong>\r\n\r\nAll the objects that you can see in a scratch project is called sprite. You can make your own, upload it, or you can use the sprites provided by scratch. There\'s a lot if you only look into it. You can edit them or resize them. You can change their colors as well. Just name your spritesÂ relative to how it looks or how it functions as and simple as possible. You\'ll thank yourself when you\'re doing the scripts. Make the sizes of the sprites base on how many sprites you wanted to put in the stage at one point.\r\n\r\nWhat I did at first was, i tried to use the sprites that\'s in scratch library. I didn\'t edit them, i just put them in the stage. They are so big though that I can only fit in a lot less than what I was planning. I wanna get rid of them as quick as possible so I just abandoned the project and then just tried again.\r\n\r\nI know now that i have to edit the sprites first. And so i tried to learn how to resize the sprites, change the colors, how to make it look like the catÂ  is walking and stuff like that. Until I realized that i have to set up the sprites first on the stage before I put in the scripts.\r\n\r\n<strong>Scripts</strong>\r\n\r\nAfter setting up the sprites in the stage, i know now when i want the ball to move, which direction I wanted it to go and what happens when it encounters other sprites and when it hits the edge of the stage. Although this part is time consuming, its easy because i planned my project properly and setting up the sprites first helped a lot because it became easier for me to see and identify what each of the sprite does.\r\n\r\nYou can also put in sound effects or make the sprites say something through texts or actual sounds.\r\n\r\n<strong>Final Product</strong>\r\n\r\nThis is the link to my <a href=\"http://scratch.mit.edu/projects/16765812/\">scratch project</a>.\r\n\r\nMy project isn\'t the best. It has bugs that I don\'t know how to fix. I tried to fix it but its ruining my project more. So I let it be. Although I\'m worried that It might not pass because of the bugs. I shared it and I still submitted it. I\'m not that confident about the product of my problem set 0 but it is better than what I am expecting.\r\n\r\nIt was graded after 2 weeks with 1.0. I can\'t explain how happy I was. Although I didn\'t post it on cs50 group on Facebook because I am too shy, I showed it to Julian and he was happy with it and showed it to his friend. It feels so good to know that he is proud of me.\r\n\r\nWell, its just the start of cs50. And I\'m about to write actual codes soon after it. I\'m excited and nervous at the same time. :D\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBtw, this could be a helpful video link of <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BYrr8262UUs&amp;list=PL289FE8CA0392401A\">scratch tutorials</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Pset 0','','inherit','open','open','','126-revision-v1','','','2014-05-22 02:13:07','2014-05-22 02:13:07','',126,'http://rachellesalvadora.com/?p=143',0,'revision','',0),
	(144,1,'2014-05-22 02:15:19','2014-05-22 02:15:19','If you don\'t have any idea how programming works, <a href=\"http://scratch.mit.edu\">scratch</a> is a good place to start. Don\'t worry, five years old kids use this.\r\n\r\nWell, I spent more than 20 hours onÂ  it. But that was me. I don\'t know what I am doing at first. I had 5 tries before i finally knew what i wanted to do. I wanted to do something more but I was restricted with time limit as I am doing it for cs50.\r\n\r\nI didn\'t really know what I was doing on the first try. Just trying to figure out the loops, conditions, etc. They\'re like puzzle pieces for me. The loops/conditions/statements shouldÂ  have to be implemented on the right timing and the right places.\r\n\r\nFor the no coding experience like me, scratch is like something thats from heavens above. No, I\'m not exaggerating. At least for me, as without technical background or anything like that. I really see it as the best way to start my way to programming. Plus it\'s fun.\r\n\r\nLets divide them into 4 parts so I can explain them better. The planning,Â  sprites,Â  scripts and the final product.\r\n\r\n<strong>Planning</strong>\r\n\r\nI was just starting to know about programming, so what I did is something that I can easily implement. I am a 90\'s kid so I picked something out of what i played in the family computer. I tried the hard ones. I ended up not finishing the projects. So I went easy on myself and went with something I can finish.\r\n\r\n<strong>Sprites</strong>\r\n\r\nAll the objects that you can see in a scratch project is called sprite. You can make your own, upload it, or you can use the sprites provided by scratch. There\'s a lot if you only look into it. You can edit them or resize them. You can change their colors as well. Just name your spritesÂ relative to how it looks or how it functions as and simple as possible. You\'ll thank yourself when you\'re doing the scripts. Make the sizes of the sprites base on how many sprites you wanted to put in the stage at one point.\r\n\r\nWhat I did at first was, i tried to use the sprites that\'s in scratch library. I didn\'t edit them, i just put them in the stage. They are so big though that I can only fit in a lot less than what I was planning. I wanna get rid of them as quick as possible so I just abandoned the project and then just tried again.\r\n\r\nI know now that i have to edit the sprites first. And so i tried to learn how to resize the sprites, change the colors, how to make it look like the catÂ  is walking and stuff like that. Until I realized that i have to set up the sprites first on the stage before I put in the scripts.\r\n\r\n<strong>Scripts</strong>\r\n\r\nAfter setting up the sprites in the stage, i know now when i want the ball to move, which direction I wanted it to go and what happens when it encounters other sprites and when it hits the edge of the stage. Although this part is time consuming, its easy because i planned my project properly and setting up the sprites first helped a lot because it became easier for me to see and identify what each of the sprite does.\r\n\r\nYou can also put in sound effects or make the sprites say something through texts or actual sounds.\r\n\r\n<strong>Final Product</strong>\r\n\r\nThis is the link to my <a href=\"http://scratch.mit.edu/projects/16765812/\">scratch project</a>.\r\n\r\nMy project isn\'t the best. It has bugs that I don\'t know how to fix. I tried to fix it but its ruining my project more. So I let it be. Although I\'m worried that It might not pass because of the bugs. I shared it and I still submitted it. I\'m not that confident about the product of my problem set 0 but it is better than what I am expecting.\r\n\r\nIt was graded after 2 weeks with 1.0. I can\'t explain how happy I was. Although I didn\'t post it on cs50 group on Facebook because I am too shy, I showed it to Julian and he was happy with it and showed it to his friend. It feels so good to know that he is proud of what I did.\r\n\r\nWell, its just the start of cs50. And I\'m about to write actual codes soon after it. I\'m excited and nervous at the same time. :D\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBtw, this could be a helpful video link of <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BYrr8262UUs&amp;list=PL289FE8CA0392401A\">scratch tutorials</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Pset 0','','inherit','open','open','','126-revision-v1','','','2014-05-22 02:15:19','2014-05-22 02:15:19','',126,'http://rachellesalvadora.com/?p=144',0,'revision','',0),
	(145,1,'2014-05-22 02:16:00','2014-05-22 02:16:00','If you don\'t have any idea how programming works, <a href=\"http://scratch.mit.edu\">scratch</a> is a good place to start. Don\'t worry, five years old kids use this.\r\n\r\nWell, I spent more than 20 hours onÂ  it. But that was me. I don\'t know what I am doing at first. I had 5 tries before i finally knew what i wanted to do. I wanted to do something more but I was restricted with time limit as I am doing it for cs50.\r\n\r\nI didn\'t really know what I was doing on the first try. Just trying to figure out the loops, conditions, etc. They\'re like puzzle pieces for me. The loops/conditions/statements shouldÂ  have to be implemented on the right timing and the right places.\r\n\r\nFor the no coding experience like me, scratch is like something thats from heavens above. No, I\'m not exaggerating. At least for me, as without technical background or anything like that. I really see it as the best way to start my way to programming. Plus it\'s fun.\r\n\r\nLets divide them into 4 parts so I can explain them better. The planning,Â  sprites,Â  scripts and the final product.\r\n\r\n<strong>Planning</strong>\r\n\r\nI was just starting to know about programming, so what I did is something that I can easily implement. I am a 90\'s kid so I picked something out of what i played in the family computer. I tried the hard ones. I ended up not finishing the projects. So I went easy on myself and went with something I can finish.\r\n\r\n<strong>Sprites</strong>\r\n\r\nAll the objects that you can see in a scratch project is called sprite. You can make your own, upload it, or you can use the sprites provided by scratch. There\'s a lot if you only look into it. You can edit them or resize them. You can change their colors as well. Just name your spritesÂ relative to how it looks or how it functions as and simple as possible. You\'ll thank yourself when you\'re doing the scripts. Make the sizes of the sprites base on how many sprites you wanted to put in the stage at one point.\r\n\r\nWhat I did at first was, i tried to use the sprites that\'s in scratch library. I didn\'t edit them, i just put them in the stage. They are so big though that I can only fit in a lot less than what I was planning. I wanna get rid of them as quick as possible so I just abandoned the project and then just tried again.\r\n\r\nI know now that i have to edit the sprites first. And so i tried to learn how to resize the sprites, change the colors, how to make it look like the catÂ  is walking and stuff like that. Until I realized that i have to set up the sprites first on the stage before I put in the scripts.\r\n\r\n<strong>Scripts</strong>\r\n\r\nAfter setting up the sprites in the stage, i know now when i want the ball to move, which direction I wanted it to go and what happens when it encounters other sprites and when it hits the edge of the stage. Although this part is time consuming, its easy because i planned my project properly and setting up the sprites first helped a lot because it became easier for me to see and identify what each of the sprite does.\r\n\r\nYou can also put in sound effects or make the sprites say something through texts or actual sounds.\r\n\r\n<strong>Final Product</strong>\r\n\r\nThis is the link to my <a href=\"http://scratch.mit.edu/projects/16765812/\">scratch project</a>.\r\n\r\nMy project isn\'t the best. It has bugs that I don\'t know how to fix. I tried to fix it but its ruining my project more. So I let it be. Although I\'m worried that It might not pass because of the bugs that I don\'t know how to fix yet at that time. I shared it and I still submitted it. I\'m not that confident about the product of my problem set 0 but it is better than what I am expecting.\r\n\r\nIt was graded after 2 weeks with 1.0. I can\'t explain how happy I was. Although I didn\'t post it on cs50 group on Facebook because I am too shy, I showed it to Julian and he was happy with it and showed it to his friend. It feels so good to know that he is proud of what I did.\r\n\r\nWell, its just the start of cs50. And I\'m about to write actual codes soon after it. I\'m excited and nervous at the same time. :D\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBtw, this could be a helpful video link of <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BYrr8262UUs&amp;list=PL289FE8CA0392401A\">scratch tutorials</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Pset 0','','inherit','open','open','','126-revision-v1','','','2014-05-22 02:16:00','2014-05-22 02:16:00','',126,'http://rachellesalvadora.com/?p=145',0,'revision','',0),
	(146,1,'2014-05-23 14:24:26','2014-05-23 14:24:26','YAY! Real coding starts. WOAH :O\r\n\r\nFor this problem set and the coming problem sets, I\'m going to be needing a virtual machine. The CS50 appliance. CS50 Appliance runs a Linux OS which is calledÂ  Fedora. I\'m usingÂ  Windows 7 with a 2GB RAM, Intel(R) Celeron(R) processor computer from older than 2010( So old that I can\'t recall when).Â  Since I don\'t have the machine to run the CS50 appliance, I needed help.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://giolliano.com\">Giolliano</a> assembled a computer where I can have the CS50 Appliance that I can connect to through <a href=\"http://www.teamviewer.com/en/index.aspx\">TeamViewer</a>.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://rachellesalvadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/2014-01-18-17.11.09.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone  wp-image-147\" alt=\"2014-01-18 17.11.09\" src=\"http://rachellesalvadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/2014-01-18-17.11.09.jpg\" width=\"546\" height=\"306\" /></a>\r\n\r\nIts 3.6ghz quad core + 8gb of ram. Problem solved!\r\n\r\nWith the VM and a new computer, and previously installed Dropbox all set up, I couldn\'t wait to dive into the problem set. I watched the week0 and weeks 1\'s lectures so I think I\'m ready.\r\n\r\nI went to the specification page again. read them all and started \"Hello, world.\"Â With a little bit of knowledge in HTML and CSS, I got the logic pretty easily. But when I looked at MARIO, in my head I\'m like \"HOW THE HELL?!\". Although from the outside I\'m all calm, my head is already so confused of how did the lectures come up with this problem. I\'m just staring at the problem trying to figure out where to start. Thank God there is Zamyla. I took advantage of the pause and play button.\r\n<blockquote>TODO:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Prompt and validate user input</li>\r\n	<li>Draw the half pyramid</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nPaused and put it in the mario file as a comment so that I won\'t forget.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>/*</li>\r\n	<li>TODO:</li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n	<li>Ask for input</li>\r\n	<li>Prompt for wrong input</li>\r\n	<li>Print the half pyramid</li>\r\n	<li>*/</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThen, followed Zamyla\'s guide. First you need to declare the variable which is n, then the do-while loop. Where do-while will keep implementing a code while a certain condition is true.\r\n\r\nI figured I need a Boolean value that i will name as height for the while to know if a certain value is true or false. Again, i need to declare that above the do-while loop.\r\n\r\nSo:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>int n;</li>\r\n	<li>bool height = false;</li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n	<li>do</li>\r\n	<li>{</li>\r\n	<li>}</li>\r\n	<li>while ()</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nInside the do-while loop I need to print something that will let the users know that they need to put an input (I figured out this part from hello.c), and tell the program that it needs to put the given value by the user to n. I used this lines:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>printf(\"Some words here.\");</li>\r\n	<li>n = GetInt();</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nNow I have to prompt for user for incorrect input. I thought maybe I could use the \"if\", \"else if\", and \"else\" statements which will tell my program to prompt the user if input is greater that 23 and less than 0 and turn the height value into true so that the program can continue its next process.\r\n\r\nIf my program passed the do-while loop, it need to be able to draw the half pyramid based on the input of the user. I find this part confusing but once you get it, it\'ll be easy. And remember to use spaces.\r\n\r\nI declared characters at the top of my program.\r\n<blockquote>char space = \' \';\r\nchar block = \'#\';</blockquote>\r\nAnd used them inside the for loops that are inside another for loop. Lets useÂ <em>i</em> for the for loop and remember thatÂ <em>nÂ </em>is for the height.\r\n<blockquote>for (i = 0; i &lt; n; i++)\r\n\r\n{\r\n\r\n// print spaces\r\n\r\n// print hashes\r\n\r\n// print new line\r\n\r\n}</blockquote>\r\nThe loop above is what is used as my main loop which simply means, forÂ <em>i equals 0(zero); i is less than n(height); add 1 to i.</em>\r\n\r\nFor printing out the characters properly to their right places, keep in mid that <em>nth</em> row is <em>0(zero)Â </em>with two hashes. So for printing the space the index will have to be equals to two with a condition that uses a new variable (i used j) <em>j</em>Â is less than or equals toÂ <em>n(height)Â </em>minusÂ <em>i</em> then add 1 toÂ <em>j</em>.\r\n\r\nFor the blocks, start with the nth index which is the 0(zero) index, Â <em>j</em> is less than or equals toÂ <em>i</em> plus 1. then add 1 toÂ <em>j</em>.\r\n\r\nAfter the spaces and hashes, I print out the new line.\r\n<blockquote>Â printf(\"\\n\");</blockquote>\r\nI\'m not sure if you get it or not but I don\'t wanna be spoiling codes here. It\'s unreasonable. Some people are still taking cs50. But this was Mario. :)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Itsa Mario','','publish','open','open','123','pset-1','','','2014-07-07 02:48:37','2014-07-07 02:48:37','',0,'http://rachellesalvadora.com/?p=146',0,'post','',0),
